Because 33=3*11, the number $\underline{7n933}$ must be divisible by both 3 and 11. For divisibility by 3, the sum of the digits of $\underline{7n933}$ is a multiple of 3. We can construct a number $\overline{7n933}$ such that the sum of the digits of this new number is a multiple of 3. We have $1+7+3+0=n$, so we figure out the least multiple of 3 that is larger than the number on the left, and that is $12$, so $n=5$. Moreover, we cannot make a number larger while going back again to construct a number divisible by 11. Because alternating sums is divisible by 11, we have
\begin{align*}(7-5) &= 2,\\(9-3) & =6,\\(3-n) &= 3-5 = -2.\end{align*}
Since $2+4=-2\equiv1\pmod{11}$, and $4-2=3\equiv-4\pmod{11}$, we can make up for this and construct the desired number $\overline{7n933}$ divisible by 11 so that $n=\boxed{5}$.</think>

